text.tspan: 1. Make your own rules:
e.g. a "once a day/week rule",
changing from larger to smaller quantities
and take the pressure off: every reduction is great!
3. If you miss the taste of meat,
you are well served with strongly spiced dishes like curries.
Also "as if" versions, for example noodles with soy Bolognese sauce
or sliced meat with seitan, are a good alternative for some people.
Others, e.g. celebrity chef Jamie Oliver prefer to cook without
trying to replace meat - because meat alternatives such as tofu etc.
are often not well received by meat eaters
2. Do not fear protein deficiency
by eating less meat!
You can still follow a healthy, balanced diet:
Legumes, vegetables, cereals and dairy products
are high-quality sources of protein.
Some of the best athletes in the world are vegans!
4. If you eat meat,
then it should be organic
and from species-appropriate, regional production,
preferably from the direct marketer.
Find out whether there are suppliers of organic meat
in your region. Make sure the animal feed is not coming
from overseas. And you just learned which animals
cause the least CO2 equivalents!
